On National Pearl Harbor Remembrance Day, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. honors the memory of the 2,403 service members and civilians who lost their lives in the tragic attack on December 7, 1941. He reflects on the resilience of America's Armed Forces and the bravery of the Greatest Generation who defended freedom and democracy during World War II. The commemoration serves as a reminder of the country's capacity to achieve triumphs even in dark times. President Biden encourages Americans to reflect on the courage shown by service members that day and express gratitude to the survivors. He urges federal agencies, organizations, groups, and individuals to fly the flag at half-staff in honor of those who died at Pearl Harbor.